AVIAN INFLUENZA, HUMAN (109) - INDONESIA, WHO
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2007
Source: World Health Organization (WHO) Epidemic and Pandemic Alert
and Response (EPR) disease outbreak news [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2007_07_11/en/index.html>

Indonesia: avian influenza situation - WHO update 12
----------------------------------------------------
As of 11 Jul 2007, the Ministry of Health of Indonesia has announced
a new case of human infection of H5N1 avian influenza. A 6-year-old
male from Banten province developed symptoms on 1 Jul 2007, and was
hospitalized on 5 Jul 2007. He died on 8 Jul 2007. The Ministry of
Health is currently investigating the source of infection.
Of the 102 cases confirmed to date in Indonesia, 81 have been fatal.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
******
[2]
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2007
Source: The Daily Telegraph online, Agence France-Presse report [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,22056048-5012773,00.html>

Indonesia: Bird flu victim had no poultry contact
-------------------------------------------------
A 6-year-old Indonesian boy who died of bird flu last weekend [8 Jul
2007] had no apparent contact with poultry, an agriculture ministry
official said. The boy from Cilegon in Banten province, just west of
the capital Jakarta, was Indonesia's 81st bird flu victim.
Contact with infected birds is the most common form of transmission
of the deadly virus to humans, experts say. Memed Zulkarnaen,
Director of the Agriculture Ministry's bird flu unit, said no
infected poultry had been found within a radius of up to 300 meters
(984 ft) from the boy's home. "The Indonesian medical community is
still puzzled and does not understand from which source the victim
was infected with the bird flu virus," he said. "We are puzzled
because the H5N1 virus needs to 'stick' to an object such as poultry
and cannot freely circulate in the air," he said.
Asked whether there was a possibility the boy had contracted the
virus from another person, Mr Zulkarnaen said it was premature to
tell and investigations involving personnel from the UN's health and
agriculture agencies were ongoing.
Sardikin Giriputro, Deputy Director of Jakarta's Sulianti Saroso
Hospital, where the boy died, said on Tue [10 Jul 2007] that the boy
had visited relatives who lived near a zoo elsewhere in Banten
province [previously identified as the Bandung Zoo - Mod.CP], 4 days
before he fell sick.
Indonesia is the nation worst hit by avian influenza. It confirmed
its 1st human case in July 2005, but the source of infection in that
particular case was never determined.
Separately, on Wed [11 Jul 2007], the national committee overseeing
Indonesia's bird flu fight along with UNICEF were to begin
distributing 7000 protective kits to villages in Banten province,
where at least 10 bird flu deaths have occurred. The kits contain
gloves, masks, soap, an informational VCD (video compact disk), a
banner, and booklet. About 100 000 kits were distributed in high-risk
areas in May [2007], a statement from the committee said.
Indonesia stepped up its campaign this year [2007] to battle bird
flu, barring Jakarta residents from the popular practice of keeping
poultry in their backyards. Officials have been criticized for being
slow to act when avian influenza 1st appeared in the archipelago nation.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall
[The statements attributed to Memed Zulkarnaen, Director of the
Agriculture Ministry's bird flu unit, are premature and should be
evaluated with caution. There may be a variety of reasons for failure
to reveal prior contacts of the deceased patient with poultry. - Mod.CP]
[Banten province, on the western end of the island of Java, just west
of the capital Jakarta, can be located on the map of Indonesia available at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/indonesi.pdf>. - CopyEd.MJ]
