[3]
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2007
Source: Departemen Kesehatan RI [edited]
<http://www.depkes.go.id/en/1007sz.htm>

Indonesia: Distribution of cases by province
-----------------------------------------------
A 6-year-old boy (SZ), who lived at Komplek BPI in Kelurahan Panggung
Rawi, Cilegon Subdistrict, Cilegon Municipality, Banten, was
positively infected by avian influenza (AI) virus, based on RT-PCR
(Real Time Polymerase Chain Reaction) Test of laboratories of the
National Board of Health Research and Development MOHRI and Eijkman
Molecular Biological Institution Jakarta, on 9 Jul 2007. This
information was received by the Center for Public Communication from
AI Post, DG of Disease Control and Environmental Health MOHRI on Mon
9 Jul 2007 [see also: Avian influenza, human (108): Indonesia
20070709.2187 and Avian influenza, human (109): Indonesia, WHO, to be
archived).
SZ had symptoms of high temperature, cough and breathing difficulty
on 1 Jul 2007. He was treated at Siloam Gleneagles Hospital on 5 Jul
2007 and then referred to Sulianti Saroso Infection Hospital, Jakarta
on the same day. On 8 Jul 2007, he died. Laboratory observation
results indicated that SZ suffered leukopenia, thrombocytopenia and
pneumonia. The risk factor is still not clear.
SZ is the 13th avian influenza positive case in Banten and the 102nd
in Indonesia (81 people have died). The Case Fatality Rate (CFR)
reaches 79.41 percent. The distribution of avian influenza sufferers
in Indonesia is presented in the following table:
Avian influenza-positive cases by Indonesian province
-----------------------------------------------
No / Province / Cases / Deaths
1 / West Java / 29 / 23
2 / DKI Jakarta / 25 / 22
3 / Banten / 13 / 11
4 / North Sumatera / 8 / 7
5 / East Java / 7 / 5
6 / Central Java / 9 / 8
7 / Lampung / 3 / 0
8 / South Sulawesi / 1 / 1
9 / West Sumatera / 3 / 1
10 / South Sumatera / 1 / 1
11 / Riau / 3 / 2
Total: 102 cases / 81 deaths
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall
[A map of Indonesia can be accessed at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/indonesi.pdf>,
showing the locations of these 11 Indonesian provinces. Human cases
of avian H5N1 influenza have not been recorded in the other 19
provinces of Indonesia. - Mod.CP]
